;; Book of Narrative Games — Chapter 4: Characters, Poses, Breath

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :chapter-number      4
  :title               "Characters, Poses, Breath"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "narrative-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + narrative-craft"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"A character with a name and a body of text is a character. A character
with a name and a body of pixels that BREATHES is a person. The
difference is not measurable in pixels or verbs. It is measurable in
what the kid does when the character leaves the room. If she looks up.
If she noticed. If she cares that the room is now empty.

We are going to give characters bodies that do the smallest, quietest
things: breathe, nod, lean, look toward the player. Not action-movie
gestures. The subtle continuous motion that says 'this thing is alive.'
Animation studios call it 'ambient motion' and it is what separates a
statue from a figure. Kids call it 'breathing' because that is what it
looks like.

The physics of body language: two pixels of vertical drift over a
one-second cycle is the difference between a mannequin and a person.

---

## 4.1 Making a character

```scheme
;; Give a name and a body to a character.
(define mira (make-character 'mira))
(entity/pose!  mira 'standing)
(entity/sprite! mira 'girl-in-blue)
(entity/set-pos! mira 200 180)
(entity/tag! mira 'friendly)
```

`make-character` gives us an entity id we can refer to by name. The
symbol `'mira` is a Scheme name; the return value is the entity id.
Elsewhere in the code, if we need to talk about Mira, we use the
variable `mira` — not the symbol.

`entity/pose!` sets the stance — standing, sitting, crouched. This
picks a sprite from the character's sprite sheet, if it has one, or
just tags the pose for later reads.

`entity/sprite!` sets which sprite to render. In the reference,
sprites are named symbols; you can put anything you want there and the
engine substitutes a placeholder shape if the name is unknown. Perfect
for prototyping.

`entity/set-pos!` puts her at pixel coordinates. `entity/tag!` adds
`'friendly` to her tag list for later `filter`ing.

Four lines. Mira exists on the page. But she does not yet breathe. Let
us fix that.

---

## 4.2 Breath

This is the single most important verb in this chapter.

```scheme
;; A gentle rise-and-fall that never stops.
(part/breathe mira 0.3)
```

That's it. `part/breathe mira 0.3` starts a slow ambient motion where
Mira's whole body rises about 2 pixels and falls about 2 pixels every
2 seconds. The 0.3 is the rate — 0.3 Hz, or about one breath every 3
seconds. Slower than a human at rest (about 0.2-0.25 Hz for adults,
faster for kids), which reads on screen as 'calm.' A character in
distress might breathe at 0.6-0.8 Hz — the same amount of movement,
just faster.

Try it. Put Mira on the page. Do not breathe her. Watch her for ten
seconds. She looks like a decal. Add `(part/breathe mira 0.3)`. Watch
her for ten seconds. You cannot look away. Your eye locks onto the
tiny rise-and-fall the way it locks onto a candle flame.

That is what animation studios pay their senior animators to do — the
breath cycle. In our runtime it is one line of Scheme.

---

## 4.3 The (part/*) family

Twelve verbs give a character everything she needs to communicate a
mood without speaking.

```scheme
(part/breathe    ent rate)              ;; ambient rise-fall
(part/nod        ent)                   ;; agreement: two quick down-ups
(part/tilt       ent degrees)           ;; head tilt for curiosity
(part/lean       ent px)                ;; body lean forward or back
(part/turn       ent direction)         ;; face left, right, front, back
(part/look-toward ent x y)              ;; eyes track a point
(part/bow        ent depth)             ;; respect
(part/wave       ent hand)              ;; greet
(part/sway       ent amount)            ;; uncertainty, thinking
(part/step       ent direction)         ;; a single step in that direction
(part/reach      ent x y)               ;; arm extends toward point
(part/expression ent emotion)           ;; face changes: happy, sad, angry
(part/shrug      ent)                   ;; don't know
```

Every one is short. Every one composes with the others. A character can
be breathing (baseline) and tilting her head (curiosity) and looking at
the player (attention) all at once. The runtime layers them.

Study the list. If you are designing a character, ask 'what does she do
when she is thinking?' Maybe she sways slightly (`part/sway mira 3`).
'What does she do when she is confused?' She tilts and looks
(`part/tilt mira 15` and `part/look-toward mira player-x player-y`).
Every character can have a signature — a combination of these gestures
that reads as HER.

---

## 4.4 A scene with body language

Let us give Mira a whole scene where her body is doing the talking.

```scheme
(define (mira-scene)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  ;; The room.
  (paint-text 20 40 \"A small back garden. Mira is looking at a book.\")

  ;; Mira's baseline: breathing, sitting.
  (entity/pose! mira 'sitting)
  (entity/set-pos! mira 240 200)
  (part/breathe mira 0.3)                    ;; slow, calm

  ;; The kid walks in.
  (world/after 60
    (lambda ()
      (part/look-toward mira 60 200)          ;; eyes track to the door
      (part/tilt mira 8)))                    ;; curiosity — head tilts

  ;; The kid says hi.
  (world/after 120
    (lambda ()
      (part/expression mira 'smile)
      (part/wave mira 'right)))                ;; a small wave

  ;; The kid asks a hard question.
  (world/after 240
    (lambda ()
      (part/tilt mira 0)                       ;; head straightens
      (part/lean mira -8)                      ;; leans back
      (part/expression mira 'thinking)
      (part/sway mira 4)))                     ;; sways gently while she thinks
  )
```

Read the code. That is a whole silent conversation. Mira is reading.
The kid walks in — Mira's eyes go to the door and her head tilts. The
kid says hi — Mira smiles and waves. The kid asks a hard question —
Mira straightens, leans back, thinks. No dialogue in this snippet at
all, and yet a scene has happened.

Now imagine putting dialogue on top. Every part-verb is punctuation.
Mira nods on 'yes.' She sways on 'I do not know.' She tilts on the
kid's confusing sentence. The words are the melody; the body is the
rhythm.

---

## 4.5 A character who reacts to the mouse

`part/look-toward` accepts any (x, y). If we pass the mouse position,
Mira watches the mouse. This is a small trick that makes a static
scene feel alive.

```scheme
;; Mira's eyes follow the pointer.
(on-frame
  (lambda ()
    (part/look-toward mira (input/mouse-x) (input/mouse-y))))
```

Every frame, Mira's eyes reposition to look where the pointer is.
Move the pointer left; her eyes go left. Move it up; her eyes go up.
This costs almost nothing and communicates 'she is aware of you' more
strongly than a whole paragraph of description.

You can also do this with the touch position on a tablet, or with the
sensed direction of a controller stick. Whatever the kid's attention
points at, Mira looks at.

Do not overuse this. If every character in the game tracks the mouse
constantly, the effect feels needy — like all the NPCs want your
attention. Use it selectively, for the character whose relationship
with the player is central to the scene.

---

## 4.6 Signatures — every character breathes differently

The bee-keeper breathes slow. The kid breathes fast. The villain
breathes slower than anyone else in the game — that is HOW he is
scary. Signatures come from the parameters.

```scheme
;; Character signatures.
(define (mira-signature)
  (part/breathe mira 0.28)                    ;; calm
  (part/sway    mira 1))                       ;; barely detectable

(define (kid-signature)
  (part/breathe kid 0.55)                     ;; excited
  (part/sway    kid 3))                        ;; fidgets

(define (villain-signature)
  (part/breathe villain 0.15)                  ;; unnervingly slow
  (part/sway    villain 0))                    ;; unmoving

(define (bee-keeper-signature)
  (part/breathe bee-keeper 0.20)               ;; slower than average
  (part/sway    bee-keeper 2))                 ;; a small ambient sway
```

The kid does not know she is decoding breath rates. She just feels
that the villain is unnerving and the kid character is nervous and
Mira is calm and the bee-keeper is slower than everyone else because
he has been breathing to that rhythm his whole life.

Set the signature ONCE when the character enters the scene. It runs
in the background for the whole scene. Layer specific gestures on top
— nods, tilts, waves — without touching the baseline. When the
character leaves, `(part/halt villain)` stops all ambient motion.

---

## 4.7 A worked scene: the meeting on the porch

Two characters. One breath rate each. A page of prose that would take
you five minutes to write and thirty seconds to read.

```scheme
(define (porch-meeting)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 20 40 \"The porch. Late afternoon. Two chairs.\")

  ;; Mira, on the left chair.
  (define mira (make-character 'mira))
  (entity/pose! mira 'sitting)
  (entity/set-pos! mira 120 180)
  (part/breathe mira 0.28)

  ;; The kid's father, on the right chair. He has not spoken in a while.
  (define father (make-character 'father))
  (entity/pose! father 'sitting)
  (entity/set-pos! father 280 180)
  (part/breathe father 0.22)

  ;; First minute: silence.
  (world/after 180
    (lambda () (paint-text 20 250 \"MIRA: 'It is a fine sky.'\")))

  ;; Father takes his time to respond.
  (world/after 300
    (lambda () (part/turn father 'left)))       ;; he turns to look at her

  (world/after 360
    (lambda ()
      (part/nod father)
      (paint-text 20 280 \"FATHER: 'It is.'\")))

  ;; A pause.
  (world/after 480
    (lambda () (paint-text 20 310 \"MIRA: 'She came home yesterday.'\")))

  ;; He does not react quickly. He stops breathing for one cycle.
  (world/after 540
    (lambda ()
      (part/halt father)                        ;; a moment without breath
      (world/after 60
        (lambda () (part/breathe father 0.22)))))

  (world/after 660
    (lambda ()
      (part/lean father -6)                     ;; leans back into the chair
      (paint-text 20 340 \"FATHER: 'Did she stay?'\")))

  (world/after 780
    (lambda ()
      (part/nod mira)
      (paint-text 20 370 \"MIRA: 'She stayed.'\")))
  )
```

That is a scene with almost no words. The father's held breath — one
line of `part/halt` — carries more than any adjective. The lean back
after the news comes carries the rest. Mira's nod at the end is a
period. Nobody said anything a screenwriter would love, but a whole
family reunion happened in eight seconds of screen time.

The kid who watches this and understands why it worked will write
better scenes forever. The kid who wrote this and got tears from a
friend who played it will write more games.

---

## 4.8 Common desktop tasks — the operator's little companion

An operator's shop has a mascot: a small cat named Yuzu. Yuzu sits
in the corner of the shop cart, breathes, occasionally looks at the
kid, occasionally does a small stretch. Yuzu is not gameplay. Yuzu is
COMPANY.

```scheme
;; Yuzu the shop cat. Ambient companion.
(define-card 'shop-with-yuzu
  :init
  (lambda ()
    (scene/imagine)
    (surface/paper)
    (paint-text 20 40 \"Welcome. Feel free to look around.\")

    (define yuzu (make-character 'yuzu))
    (entity/sprite! yuzu 'cat-orange)
    (entity/set-pos! yuzu 400 300)
    (part/breathe yuzu 0.35)                    ;; cats breathe faster than us

    ;; Every 15-25 seconds, Yuzu looks at the mouse.
    (define (yuzu-attention)
      (part/look-toward yuzu (input/mouse-x) (input/mouse-y))
      (world/after (+ 900 (random 600))       ;; 15-25s at 60fps
        (lambda () (yuzu-attention))))
    (yuzu-attention)

    ;; Every 30-60 seconds, Yuzu does a small stretch.
    (define (yuzu-stretch)
      (part/reach yuzu (entity/x yuzu) (- (entity/y yuzu) 20))
      (world/after 30 (lambda () (part/halt yuzu)))
      (world/after 30 (lambda () (part/breathe yuzu 0.35)))
      (world/after (+ 1800 (random 1800))
        (lambda () (yuzu-stretch))))
    (yuzu-stretch)))
```

Yuzu does nothing gameplay-relevant. Ever. She just breathes and
occasionally looks at the pointer and occasionally stretches. Customers
who visit the shop feel a small warmth without being able to name
why. That is Yuzu.

Companies once paid millions for animated logo mascots that did less
than this. An operator with fifty lines of Scheme has one that does
more. That is the leverage.

---

## 4.9 Routing patterns — grouping characters by scene

When a scene has three characters, do NOT re-spawn them every frame.
Spawn once at scene entry; halt when the scene ends. Otherwise you
leak entities and their breath-timers pile up.

```scheme
(define scene-characters '())

(define (add-character-to-scene c)
  (set! scene-characters (cons c scene-characters)))

(define (end-scene-clear-characters)
  (for-each part/halt scene-characters)
  (for-each entity/despawn! scene-characters)
  (set! scene-characters '()))

;; Every scene ends with:
(end-scene-clear-characters)
```

Halt breath, despawn entities, reset the list. If you skip this you
will notice the game slowly getting laggier over an hour of play —
every scene's ghost characters still breathing off-screen. Rookie
mistake, easy fix.

---

## 4.10 Closing

You made a character breathe. You gave her a body. You wrote a scene
where two people had a hard conversation using seven part-verbs and
almost no words. That is what body language buys you.

Any character in your story from here on breathes. If she does not
breathe, she is furniture. Cortex tells you WHO she is. Breath tells
the kid that she IS.

Chapter 5 gives her a mouth — full dialogue trees. Now that her body
is alive, her words matter more.")
